'''Frances MacKeith''' (March 28, 1914 - December 14, 2011) was a British peace advocate.

==Biography==
MacKeith was born on March 28, 1914 in [[Young, New South Wales]]. Her father, [[Millais Culpin]], and mother were both doctors, and travelled with her extensively. In 1931, they attended a Nazi rally in Berlin. Five years later, she graduated from [[University College London]] with a degree in German. In 1938, MacKeith married Stephen MacKeith, and had six children.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/2012/jan/30/frances-mackeith-obituary|title=Frances MacKeith obituary|last=Tomic|first=Alice|date=2012-01-30|work=The Guardian|access-date=2018-01-13|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>

A German teacher for much of her life, MacKeith also advocated for peace during the [[Aldermaston Marches]] in the 1950s and demonstrations against the Vietnam War in [[Grosvenor Square]] in the 1960s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://peacemuseum.org.uk/object-of-the-month-blog-october-wicker-basket/|title=Object of the Month Blog – Wicker Basket » The Peace Museum|website=peacemuseum.org.uk|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-01-13}}</ref> After the protests, she joined the [[Quakers]], and continued to protest war. MacKeith worked against the [[Trident nuclear programme]] and taught prisoners in [[Winchester Prison]]. She died December 14, 2011.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.peacenews.info/node/6554/frances-mackeith-28-march-1914-14-december-2011|title=Frances MacKeith, 28 March 1914 - 14 December 2011 {{!}} Peace News|website=www.peacenews.info|language=en|access-date=2018-01-13}}</ref> MacKeith was arrested over five times.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailyecho.co.uk/news/5585570.GRAN__89__IS_JAILED/|title=GRAN, 89, IS JAILED|website=Daily Echo|language=en|access-date=2018-01-13}}</ref>

